<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="12"
  data-post-negative="-3"
  data-post-positive="15"
  data-post-id="26369099" data-poster-id="337258" id="comment-26369099">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="chipmunkofdoom2"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=337258&amp;sid=bc0216a5256140675548100709fda8f2">chipmunkofdoom2</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praetorian</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/how-the-worlds-first-bitcoin-bank-was-robbed-blind/?comments=1&post=26369099#comment-26369099" title="2014-03-05T10:06:03-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 05, 2014 10:06 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26368967#p26368967" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">shawnce</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">How do you not have virtual circuit breakers and throttling in place in a new system like this? They should have existed and been setup to trigger to easily during the early days until you vette things in the real world.<br /><br />(...the goal being to slow attacks like this down closer to human time so you can analyze and take action)<br /><br /><img src="//cdn.arstechnica.net/civis/images/smilies/sad.png" alt=":(" title="Frown" /><br /><br />...of course the flaw read to be something that a security minded professional would have designed to prevent.</div><br /><br />This is very similar to what happened to Mt Gox. The software system paid no attention to the balance of the main Bitcoin hot wallet or vault, but instead relied on other cursory and less reliable indicators as to whether the user received their funds. <br /><br />Mt Gox relied on a transaction ID to determine whether or not a payment was made. All a user has to do is change some insignificant portion of the time in the transaction, and the entire transaction ID changes. Still a valid transaction, payout still happens, but the software doesn't realize it because the transaction ID has changed.<br /><br />Though I can see why you may want to use an identifier such as the transaction ID to determine if a user was paid or not, it's downright moronic to pay no attention to your main wallet &quot;vault&quot; balance when determining if a user got paid. Also questionable is why you would allow thousands of transactions to be submitted by one user to your software in such a short period.<br /><br />Poor software design, plain and simple.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
