<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment star read"
  data-post-score="34"
  data-post-negative="-1"
  data-post-positive="35"
  data-post-id="26369343" data-poster-id="337258" id="comment-26369343">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="chipmunkofdoom2"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=337258&amp;sid=bc0216a5256140675548100709fda8f2">chipmunkofdoom2</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Praetorian</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/how-the-worlds-first-bitcoin-bank-was-robbed-blind/?comments=1&post=26369343#comment-26369343" title="2014-03-05T10:29:17-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 05, 2014 10:29 am</a>
        
          <span class="highlight reader-fav">Reader Fav</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26369121#p26369121" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">bh5505</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Does anyone know the degree to which these bitcoin operators are subjected to or otherwise obtain independent audits of their financials, internal controls, or operational security? I feel like these situations are rooted in the fact that on one side, bitcoin is all very (relatively) new and technically complex; however, the organizations themselves may not be apply the old &amp; stuffy (yet effective) financial controls that are typically utilized in corporations and banks to combat these risks.</div><br /><br />In my opinion, three things are lacking. First is knowledge of the protocol (see Mt Gox not realizing there are many legitimate reasons a transaction ID may change before it reaches the blockchain, and checking transaction IDs as a method to see if a user was paid is a horrible idea).<br /><br />Second is regulations ensuring these exchanges and &quot;banks&quot; are held accountable if anything goes wrong. Now, there are none. Regulation might be a hassle sometimes, but it sure does seem to work well in the banking system in the US.<br /><br />Third is the lack of financial recourse and psuedo-nonymous nature of the protocol. While Bitcoin is not fully anonymous, as in you can trace the path of every single coin through the blockchain, it is psuedo-nonymous. You know in which wallets the coins have been and where they went, but not who owns the wallets in question. <br /><br />Say someone fraudulently uses your credit card. You call your bank and tell them, they reverse the charge, you get your money back. The bank then goes after the retailer where the transaction was done. The bank either then denies the charge and doesn't pay the retailer, or asks for the fraudulent transaction balance back. The retailer then pursues the thief that used the fraudulent credit card through whatever means necessary. In this and most other fiat currency fraud, you know to whom the money went. When your credit card has a $500 charge on it that you didn't do, your bank knows who the payment was sent to. They go to that party and ask for the money back. <br /><br />If your Bitcoins are stolen, you know the address they went to, but that helps very little in figuring out to whom the BTC went. You have a number, not an identity. There's no way to know who owns that address. Even if there was, Bitcoin laundering services exist that accept Bitcoin payments, send those bitcoins as miniscule fractions through a huge network of random wallets (perhaps even many one time use wallets), then sends money back to the launderer. In a good system, none of the original bitcoins are sent to the BTC launderer, meaning that if you're tracing the bitcoins you once owned, chances are the person stole them doesn't even own them anymore.<br /><br />With the various ways that exist to set up a company that put almost none of the liability on the owner (LLC, Limited, etc), it's going to be difficult to set up a Bitcoin ecosystem where the BTC bank has to pay if they lose the BTC. Regulation could make this mandatory, but then nobody would get into the business of BTC banking or exchanging: such a regulation would make it very unattractive to run this type of service.<br /><br />I don't know if we'll ever be able to work through this problem. Really the only way to do so would be to start making the addresses identifiable, or link them to an identity upon creation. The whole premise of the Bitcoin protocol, however, is that the addresses are simply numbers. Aside from making the protocol extremely unattractive to a sizable amount of its current user base, adding identity info to public and private addresses is definitely not possible in the current implementation of the protocol.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=337258&amp;sid=bc0216a5256140675548100709fda8f2">chipmunkofdoom2</a> on Wed Mar 05, 2014 10:32 am</p>
      
    </div>
    <footer>
