<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment star read"
  data-post-score="45"
  data-post-negative="0"
  data-post-positive="45"
  data-post-id="26369743" data-poster-id="355975" id="comment-26369743">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="TheThirdDictor"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=355975&amp;sid=bc0216a5256140675548100709fda8f2">TheThirdDictor</a></span><span class="rank">Wise, Aged Ars Veteran</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/how-the-worlds-first-bitcoin-bank-was-robbed-blind/?comments=1&post=26369743#comment-26369743" title="2014-03-05T11:04:11-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 05, 2014 11:04 am</a>
        
          <span class="highlight reader-fav">Reader Fav</span>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26369121#p26369121" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">bh5505</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Does anyone know the degree to which these bitcoin operators are subjected to or otherwise obtain independent audits of their financials, internal controls, or operational security? I feel like these situations are rooted in the fact that on one side, bitcoin is all very (relatively) new and technically complex; however, the organizations themselves may not be apply the old &amp; stuffy (yet effective) financial controls that are typically utilized in corporations and banks to combat these risks.</div><br /><br />This has been my concern for a while. I have been an IT auditor for 10 years, and I can't tell you the number of times that I would ask a question in an audit (like &quot;What methods do you have in place to moderate requests in unstable conditions, like unusual floods of requests? What does your &quot;normal&quot; transaction volume look like? How would you know if it was different?&quot;) that the auditee had never considered. <br /><br />Nothing against them. That is part of the point of an audit. Before I was an auditor, I was an IT manager (at a bank) and sat on the other side, silently thinking &quot;Damn. Why didn't I think about that?&quot; during an audit. <br /><br />The problem is that audits suck. And everyone hates them (despite their value), and unless you are *forced* to have them? You probably won't. Hence an inherent problem with such an unregulated system. Besides, do you *want* to pay $10,000 for a decent CISA to come in and &quot;waste&quot; your staff's time for a week? Do you *want* your network admins whining about how much time it is taking them to produce all of your IDS logs for the last 3 months? And, of course, do you *really* want to know the results, if knowing them means you have to spend $250k fixing problems?<br /><br />If nobody is &quot;forcing&quot; you to do it, why would you? And what does this mean for the future of these kinds of organizations? Want to be a &quot;bank&quot; in the US? The FDIC is going to force you to go through audits every three years (or more frequently). Want to be a &quot;bank&quot; in the bitcoin world? Who has the authority to make you do *anything*?
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=355975&amp;sid=bc0216a5256140675548100709fda8f2">TheThirdDictor</a> on Wed Mar 05, 2014 11:08 am</p>
      
    </div>
