<li class="thin-divide-bottom comment neutral read"
  data-post-score="3"
  data-post-negative="-2"
  data-post-positive="5"
  data-post-id="26369807" data-poster-id="171943" id="comment-26369807">
  <header class="byline">
    
    <span class="author" data-post-author="Bobson"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=171943&amp;sid=bc0216a5256140675548100709fda8f2">Bobson</a></span><span class="rank">Ars Centurion</span>
      <aside class="icons">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2014/03/how-the-worlds-first-bitcoin-bank-was-robbed-blind/?comments=1&post=26369807#comment-26369807" title="2014-03-05T11:09:01-06:00" class="timeago datetime">Wed Mar 05, 2014 11:09 am</a>
        
        <span class="hidden-icon-start"></span>
        
      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      It seems to me that the fundamental flaw in their system was simply <span style="font-style: italic">having</span> a hot wallet.  Likewise for Mt. Gox.  Both chose speed over accuracy (even if thoughtlessly), and suffered for it.<br /><br />To the best of my knowledge (and I'm no expert), if they set up their system such that people didn't expect instant transfers, and they didn't update balances until the transfer had been confirmed enough times in the block chain, these kinds of attacks couldn't happen.  Sure, it might take a while before you got your money out, but it'd be secure.<br /><br />That would be more akin to writing checks than using an electronic transfer, but it's not a bad model.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
      <aside class="vote">
        
        <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/ucp.php?mode=login&amp;return_to=http%3A%2F%2Farstechnica.com%2Finformation-technology%2F2014%2F03%2Fhow-the-worlds-first-bitcoin-bank-was-robbed-blind%2F%3Fcomments%3D1%26amp%3Bstart%3D0%23comment-26369807" class="vote_login vote_up_login" title="Login to vote up">up</a>
        (
