    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26369633#p26369633" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Mister E. Meat</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Now I'll grant that I don't understand the scope of their issue fully but the basics of this is second semester computer science stuff.  I remember coding an &quot;ATM&quot; that had to conform to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ACID" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">ACID</a>.  There are whole systems that come with ACID built-in.</div><br />ACID has traditionally been the foundation of all database operations. The advent of massive online, high volume technologies like Facebook and other services, there has been a lot of use of &quot;eventually consistent&quot; and other non-ACID databases as a way of dealing with heavy volume of transactions. I would be surprised if this is what is going here in the case of banking, however. As you said, banking is the classic example of when you absolutely need ACID transactions. I cant imagine a bank making the decision to sacrifice ACID protection for performance.
      
    </div>
    <footer>
